Smith & Wesson 629-4 (44Mag)

It is in excellent condition.

- Stainless
- 4" barrel
- Magnaported (from the factory)
- Target Trigger / Target Hammer
- White Square Adjustable Rear Sight (Windage / Elevation)
- Red Ramp Front Sight
- No Internal Lock
- Black Rubber Stock Grips

It is an accurate and smooth shooter. The magnaports make the recoil very manageable.

Based on the research I have done it was manufactured in the mid 90s. It is in a blue box, so that puts it on the shelf around 96. It does not have the internal lock so manufacture date was before 97.

In 1999, S&W discontinued the model 29. It has been released since then in limited production as the Classic Model with a really nice key lock on the left side. "According to Paul Pluff, S&W director of marketing, 'We do not have any new model 29s that have been recently or are going to be released. ' " ~American Rifleman, August 2013~

title: For Sale:  Winchester model 94 in 30 WCF
postcontent:
Very nice pre-war, pre-'64 example of the classic 'gun that won the west' chambered for Winchester's 30 WCF (Winchester Center Fire). This round was later chambered by Marlin which designated it the .30-30 using the black powder cartridge nomenclature (the caliber is the first number and the grains of powder is the second). Marlin used this nomenclature so as to not promote its competitor's products. The 30-30 name finally became synonymous with the cartridge and Winchester ultimately dropped the 30 WCF nomenclature.
   No rust or pitting.  Receiver, barrel bands, & butt plate have matured to a nice patina and the barrel still maintains most of it's blueing.  Gun was manufactured in either 1934 (as per CFM = Cody Firearms Museum) or in 1935 (as per Madis).

title: For Sale:  Hawkins style 50 caliber muzzle loader made by Connecticut Valley Arms
postcontent:
I have a Hawkins style 50 caliber muzzle loader made by Connecticut Valley Arms; this rifle has the wooden stock not nylon, with quick disconnect sling swivel studs mounted (there are a couple of places on the stock that needs re-finishing).

 This was my first Black power rifle and at $100.00 and thought I was getting a good deal! But the sights were missing ($35.00 from CVA); the ram rod was missing ($25.00 at WalMart).  That put me having $160.00 in it right off the bat, then I had to buy powder and bullets

Several of my buddies had muzzle loaders and I just did not like the raw powder (it spilt everywhere) and having to lube the patch before inserting the ball, forget it.

I found some 250 grain bullets & sabots (I think) at WalMart, these were new to the market at the time and I believe I gave $21.00 or $22.00 for them. After shooting the rifle a couple of times I was impressed and went back and bought two more packs of bullets & sabots, the 12 pack of 250 grain power point aerotip bullets is still un-opened. There is also 10 – 300 grain bullet’s & sabots (My wife’s uncle has seen Elk on his farm and I was hoping to use these to harvest one). There are several powder pellets still in tubes that came with some of the bullets plus I bought a new box of Proxen 50 grain Proxed powder pellets ($30.00). 

The first couple of times I trided to shoot the rifle I had a misfire, the rifle came with #11 percussion caps and it turned out that they were not hot enough to ignite the pellets reliability. So I bought bigger / hotter # 10 nipples, there is one on the rifle and two new ones still in the pack, along with a new box of CCI percussion caps (might be 6 or 8 missing).

There is also a Thompsons Black Powder cleaning and a powder horn. To carry all the accessories I have an old military pouch I use for a possible bag, for the rifle there is a zippered camo rifle carrying case made by Allen Co.

Back to the powder horn; it is a real powder horn but because I use the powder pellets and I’ve just never fooled with it so for now it’s for looks only.  Also for looks are two knives ($22.00 each from Smokey Mt. Knife Works) these knives have fake Damascus blades and plastic handles. I had hoped to make new handles and sheaths from dear hide and horns. But became disabled instead.

I have $160.00 in the rifle, the bullets, powder, sights & cleaning kit, knives etc. I’m guessing I have around $250.00 / $260.00 in the accessories, making a total investment of around $420.00 (max) in the rifle.

Asking $300.00

May trade to 12 gauge pump OR
